        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Band 9 observations are critical for our scientific objectives, even
though restricted in schedulability due to the required optimal
weather conditions.  At z=2.128, band 9 probes the dust continuum at a
rest-wavelength of 140 micron.

Monte Carlo simulations in which we fit artificially noised band 9+6
photometry of modified black bodies with a range of temperatures
demonstrate that we can recover dust temperatures and gas masses,
derived through the dust method, to within 0.1 dex given 5sigma
photometry in each of the two bands (see Section 4.5 in Genzel et
al. 2015).  This is adequate to reach our scientific objectives.
While a band 10 + band 6 combination would offer a longer wavelength
baseline, reaching the required sensitivity in band 10 would be
prohibitively expensive.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The requested resolution of 0.5" is demanded by the internal structure
of our target, in order to adequately identify and disentangle the
central region, outer disk and off-center clumps, for which we aim to
constrain the bolometric star formation rate and obscuration.  In
H-band light, our target has a semi-major axis length of 5.7 kpc and
axial ratio of 0.6.  Given the negative color gradient (i.e., red
center), the size increases when measured at shorter wavelengths, with
blue off-center clumps spread over a total extent of 2" (17 kpc) along
the major axis.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Adopting the formal best-fit dust temperature of 38 K, the total
infrared luminosity of 10^12 Lsun corresponds to a galaxy-integrated
band 9 flux density of 2.9 mJy.  Assuming the spatial distribution of
the infrared luminosity is clumpy, peaking at the locations of the 4
clumps seen in UV emission, we expect peak flux densities per 0.5"
beam of around 0.7 mJy.  ALMA in cycle 3 has sufficient sensitivity to
map this at the 5sigma level (i.e., with a sensitivity per pointing of
0.14 mJy) in 2.3 hours on source (4.65 hours total).  The alternative
scenario, in which the blue off-center clumps are merely holes in the
dust and the majority of infrared emission originates from the central
1-2 beam areas of the galaxy, would yield an even higher level of
significance in the same observing time.  In a scenario where the
distribution is smoother, with 60% of the infrared luminosity in a
diffuse component, the corresponding flux measurements per beam are
expected to be at the ~3 sigma level, in which case we will extract
statistically more robust results by stacking the galaxy center, outer
disk and clump regions separately in a similar fashion as successfully
applied by Wuyts et al. (2012, 2013).

We note that the dust temperature of 38 K is poorly constrained by the
depth of the Herschel/SPIRE data, and colder dust temperatures are
formally allowed by the fit.  Magnelli et al. (2014) finds a
characteristic dust temperature of 32 K for galaxies of similar
redshift, mass and star formation rate as CDFS-2954.  Applying this
colder dust temperature, anticipated band 9 flux densities increase by
a factor 1.6.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
