    <prp:abstract>We propose to obtain deep, high-resolution dust continuum imaging in
band 9 and 6 of a star-forming clumpy disk at z=2.128.  Located in the
Hubble Ultra Deep Field, these far-infrared maps together with the
deepest rest-UV imaging ever taken, will yield the first bolometric
star formation rate distribution on sub-galactic scales of a normal
galaxy during the peak of cosmic star formation.  It will allow us to
calibrate extinction corrections to the resolved Halpha and UV
emission, and to address the nature of clumps in marginally stable
disks.  Spatial variations in the amplitude and color of the
far-infrared emission will further shed light on dust temperature,
dust column, and depletion time variations between the galaxy center
and off-center clumps.  We will test the presence of resolved
equivalents to well-known galaxy-integrated scaling relations: Tdust -
sSFR, IRX - beta, \SIGMA_SFR - \SIGMA_gas, and \tau - \SIGMA_dust.
Our study will provide unique insights into the regulation of star
formation and internal dust properties within early disks.  Lessons on
spatial Tdust variations will be of direct relevance to many band 6
and 7 imaging campaigns of larger samples.</prp:abstract>
